C10F0EAEF27140F9A5A480C5AFFD9CBF.description: Four- and Five-Year-Olds: Increasingly use words instead of actions to express their emotions

ED5EFC122FDE4E1B9C975033C2F35B1C.description: Four- and Five-Year-Olds: May still have difficulty regulating strong emotions

7A6702F054C44D47A11DC3DFF9B1D8DA.description:
Three Years: Begin to respond to an adult’s
cues about regulating their
emotions (E.g. At drop-off
time, Sage begins to control
his crying when his teacher
says, “I know you’re sad,
would you like to see what
your friends are doing?”)

30B65A8CF38F4D3E9678545F13837DAC.description:
Thirty Months to
Three Years: Begin using words to describe
their feelings while still
expressing strong emotions

25221DF6FF4E4C77A2EFEF71CEBFFC0B.description:
Twenty-Four to
Thirty Months: Have difficulty regulating strong
feelings

76CD4337BB7C4DF38929EE456A0B861E.description:
Eighteen to
Twenty-Four Months: Use comfort objects or certain
behaviors to calm themselves
(E.g. Finn finds and holds his
blanket to calm himself.)

4F1F8FA8D8E34258A4083BDE5144DD22.description:
Nine Months to
Eighteen Months
: Follow their caregiver to keep
him/her in sight

498C6B5D478A4057B5D53F6A96E4E58A.description:
Birth to
Nine Months: By 9 months, stop crying when
their needs are met or they
expect their needs to be met

9B60763BD00D4C60B4EAADC8DB6576A1.description: Four- and Five-Year-Olds: Explore emotions in various ways (through play, art, music, and dance)

ADE6B8F0AE99497D896DB1093722EA58.description:
Four- and Five-Year-Olds: Demonstrate increasing competencies in recognizing and describing their own
emotions

21DB4ED01667458CAEE5BD2C553EB468.description:
Three Years: Express their feelings verbally
with greater frequency

FCE791047B784B8CBCE8B1A6D9630B17.description:
Thirty Months to
Three Years: Verbally relate their needs,
wants, and feelings to others

E16D7A74AEFD46C898C23538B0F7C585.description:
Twenty-Four to
Thirty Months: Share their feelings through
talking and pretend play

54A5108727824FBC92F2574F052DA027.description:
Eighteen to
Twenty-Four Months: May express their feelings
strongly including extended
episodes and may not be easily
distracted

DE9436C4C235471083475F5C89448DC6.description:
Nine Months to
Eighteen Months
: Begin to express a variety of
feelings through vocalizations,
facial expressions, and body
movements

65324E2ACB13469E921F8388F12451C3.description:
Birth to
Nine Months: Express enjoyment and
unhappiness in their
environment

7F70DE9AF35D434580FF6C697B6CE426.description:
Four- and Five-Year-Olds: Begin to be able to stop undesirable behaviors on their own or with a gentle
reminder (E.g. Xavier starts to grab Zach’s car, but stops himself and asks, “Can
I use that when you’re done?”)

EA9B95A3A048494CB2D3F32A17F2D2C9.description:
Three Years: Follow classroom rules and
routines with guidance

E2A75D98005F4492A3E97525254597F0.description:
Thirty Months to
Three Years: Show increased self-regulation
and awareness of how their
actions affect others

AA92FF97FCBF41A9B005F523232DBE37.description:
Twenty-Four to
Thirty Months: With adult guidance, can begin to
tone down aggressive behaviors.

9AFDEB15176A4370964EC9AF8A0E2791.description:
Eighteen to
Twenty-Four Months: With guidance, demonstrate
they can use some classroom
materials appropriately (E.g.
The teacher shows her toddlers
how to handle books gently and
Clara turns the pages carefully.)

3D051A7A9C364BE69924119D991AD1A0.description:
Nine Months to
Eighteen Months
: Need adult support to regulate
physical expressions of emotions
(E.g. Marigold pulls another
baby’s hair until the teacher
takes her hand and shows her
how to pat the baby gently.)

AFA649328458434CB96A7FBF293C0BD9.description:
Birth to
Nine Months: Calm themselves (E.g.
9-month-old Vinod babbles in
his crib until his father comes
to get him up from his nap.)

7EDAFCD6BF7F4E25A15AADF9DE518016.description:
Four- and Five-Year-Olds:  Begin to understand the reasons for others’ emotions and respond appropriately
(E.g. Audrey says to a friend who is upset over not getting the toy she wanted
during play, “You’ll get to play with it next time.”)

E4BC47AD5AE148C6AF078C6F76CDF6BD.description:
Three Years: Begin to label others’ feelings
and recognize reasons for
those feelings

B39B736B931E41C092DCDFB3485490A3.description:
Thirty Months to
Three Years: Begin to display empathy
towards other children

25FA4022F6CD46A580723D822629F9E0.description:
Twenty-Four to
Thirty Months: May try to comfort children who
are distressed (E.g. Filomena
gives her teddy bear to Ellen,
who is crying.)

91DE5F23DDBD45E0B81970CF3FD2DBBE.description:
Eighteen to
Twenty-Four Months: Demonstrate interest in the
feelings of another child

ABD23CAFF3D84FEC8EBA636FD69DFB0A.description:
Nine Months to
Eighteen Months
: Show awareness in other
people’s emotions

09D5DA7239194DEFB0BB085481D4FBE0.description:
Birth to
Nine Months: May cry when another baby
cries

C8B5D9B4253540E2847F1A5A436432A5.description:
Four- and Five-Year-Olds: Develop friendships, sometimes based on shared interests or
characteristics

522378663B0249D8A642DDD6D62A04BD.description:
Four- and Five-Year-Olds: Sustain interaction by cooperating, helping, sharing, and expressing interest,
though they may need adult guidance

4A030CB96E644226B5938EF7B626F76B.description:
Four- and Five-Year-Olds: Build skills needed to participate successfully as a member of a group, such as
taking turns

AF39D105ADEC4FF799FCA435387CCBFB.description: Four- and Five-Year-Olds: Approach others with expectations of positive interactions

691CAF8BFAA6437FA9E1B505B53A0F7F.description:
Three Years: Play cooperatively with other
children and show preference
for some children over
others (E.g. Jose and Chris
are playing together. When
Martin comes over, Chris says,
“No, go away.”)

7258148E0DD64EF980E1ED5739ECB2B2.description:
Thirty Months to
Three Years: Begin to play cooperatively for
brief periods with other children

3CB10C7BCBD04DEFB8BD82256E8E9144.description:
Twenty-Four to
Thirty Months: Engage in brief or momentary
interactions with other children,
but may need adult support
(E.g. Siddarth yells, “Run, run,”
to several other children on the
playground.)

867FF20C3DD34F3E86B29279A58151CD.description:
Eighteen to
Twenty-Four Months: Play alongside other children,
with or without acknowledging
their presence

745C10423EA1498C8C87594B937C0E02.description:
Nine Months to
Eighteen Months
: Show interest in other children

3FE4CE26FE3A4A8BB7DB6E63E67D3F06.description:
Birth to
Nine Months: Demonstrate increasing
awareness of other children
(E.g. While lying on a blanket
close to her, Carlos reaches
for Becca’s arm.)

7710966B7E6C44AA9102B856505047F3.description:
Relationships and
social skills with
peers

B5F14C4A83884982896F8B68ADEACA87.description:
Three Years: May initiate contact with
unfamiliar adults, when
familiar adults are nearby

9B0C153435394691B7012856D101EC3C.description:
Thirty Months to
Three Years: Are more comfortable around
unfamiliar adults

749B9EF3628A40DFBE6797F9D5848742.description:
Twenty-Four to
Thirty Months: Dependent on experience, may
show more interest in unfamiliar
adults, but are still cautious

4AA76FD7437A4D93B6EF83399500788C.description:
Eighteen to
Twenty-Four Months: Continue to show hesitation
around unfamiliar adults (E.g.
Billie hides behind his father
when the store clerk says “hi”
to him.)

9BD052C3A64C4A12BAFFF04DEA77361C.description:
Nine Months to
Eighteen Months
: Show strong preference
for familiar adults and may
demonstrate fear or rejection
responses to unfamiliar adults

CC3063269BB947ED94C00B8920B46D5F.description:
Birth to
Nine Months: Are able, over time, to
differentiate between familiar
and unfamiliar adults

5F3A82974C5C4DEB80D842834106FB47.description: Four- and Five-Year-Olds:  Imitate familiar adults in culturally appropriate ways in everyday situations

F286B65AC81143B19BA9D0D1C70B9CDF.description:
Four- and Five-Year-Olds: Seek adult help when needed for emotional support, physical assistance, social
interaction, and approval

4D1F09D83CF648FD934AE3820693936E.description:
Four- and Five-Year-Olds: Interact easily with familiar adults, but may be hesitant to approach or respond
to less familiar adults

EF7AE53519634ED99331BFD5E1F29486.description:
Three Years: Respond appropriately to
social and emotional cues of
adults

57BE756F2E7F4974A41551241B51EB88.description:
Thirty Months to
Three Years: Continue to need adult approval
and validation but show more
competence

2A09855AF3BE4DA5829CE42864EE1B61.description:
Twenty-Four to
Thirty Months: Imitate and attempt to please
familiar adults (E.g. Rylee joins
in singing when her caregiver
sings a silly song with her.)

2FACD498E1674BBABC596AEE013BCB4C.description:
Eighteen to
Twenty-Four Months: Continue to need the security of
a trusted adult; ask for help, if
needed, in verbal and non-verbal
ways

1357E6CA3D014E4F82F854E722821F18.description:
Nine Months to
Eighteen Months
: Rely on trusted adults to feel
secure trying new activities

2EBCF5C876B04B47A1840A0DC067E5B9.description:
Birth to
Nine Months: Demonstrate interest in
familiar adults and develop
strong attachment to primary
caregivers

69E6D86488CF4D3EAE41A736C8D38A8A.description:
Four- and Five-Year-Olds:  Express or describe their own characteristics and preferences (E.g. Jacob only
chooses brown sweatpants when clothes shopping with his mother.)

D37A2139FA48476995D58F6CF3E396E8.description:
Four- and Five-Year-Olds:  Notice differences and make comparisons between their physical characteristics
and others’ and the way things are done in different settings (E.g. Consuela
says “My abuela talks Spanish and my grandma talks English.”)

441603C8EF5646BE83ADADB708D83E98.description:
Three Years: Continue to develop
awareness of differences and
their own gender and cultural
identity (E.g. Delia says to her
teacher, “I’m a girl, so I can
be a mommy someday.”)

D32139AC00D14733B14ACB1EBA516601.description:
Thirty Months to
Three Years: Identify or point to characters
that resemble themselves or
their family members in books
or magazines

8C00FBC854034D33A913E16A5E0EF3A6.description:
Twenty-Four to
Thirty Months: Point out or comment on
differences in gender and
physical characteristics, using
social labels (E.g. Eddie points
to each classmate and labels
each as “boy” or “girl.”)

5944E89CE6D04AB88FECB896367F76E6.description:
Eighteen to
Twenty-Four Months: Mimic adult behavior and
responses to other people

508C377FC544478E9D3958641CC8BCE6.description:
Nine Months to
Eighteen Months
: Show preference for their family
members and primary caregivers

29CAACFBE5904F968C8B10718F5D56D3.description:
Birth to
Nine Months: By 9 months, recognize that
they are separate and distinct
from primary caregivers (E.g.
8-month-old Taniesha cries
whenever her mother leaves
the room.)

14CD5370412C48B49A1635E14E2083A5.description: Four- and Five-Year-Olds:  Are confident, self-directed, purposeful and inventive in play

166C581750A94EAC8CBF39470B6105D7.description:
Three Years: Begin to experiment with
their own potential and show
confidence in their own
abilities

B7BDD45DD07A4CF8BD8BAD8CA86598B4.description:
Thirty Months to
Three Years: Show independence and
competence

1F465E9B46404F008C5A0558254E1E8D.description:
Twenty-Four to
Thirty Months: Perform the tasks requested
of them and may initiate tasks
on their own (E.g. Kyle’s nana
spoons food onto his plate
and Kyle says, “Me do it!” and
reaches for the spoon.)

56AF442CEAC145708216E841BA04EDC8.description:
Eighteen to
Twenty-Four Months: Show more awareness of their
abilities

CE1379689A1D4B5FBEF8FE8F66E1BE9E.description:
Nine Months to
Eighteen Months
: Take actions in the expectation
of getting a response from
an adult (E.g. 11-monthold Carolyn lifts her arms up
knowing that her caregiver will
pick her up.)

02ED29E5816B457CA458985434DDC4C1.description:
Birth to
Nine Months: Smile and laugh when
imitating an adult
(E.g. 8-month-old Ashton
smiles when he imitates his
teacher clapping.)

8DB2956310DB4BCCBB8A88AF19BB8A32.description:
Boast about what they know and can do (E.g. Quinn says, “I am really good at
drawing rainbows.”)

9D12D8CD249A47FC8757392C78A4CACD.description: Four- and Five-Year-Olds: Continue to seek adult attention and recognition of what they know and can do

D281B85A11EA4BDAAF5986F5034A008C.description:
Three Years: Draw adult’s attention to their
actions and creations (E.g. On
the playground Luna keeps
telling her father, “Watch me,
watch me!”)

E692886842B1483CA5D2FAC325B3A2A9.description:
Thirty Months to
Three Years: Call attention to themselves in
photographs or videos

2078E03058804C5F8EE263F130F2B126.description:
Twenty-Four to
Thirty Months: Show delight in their abilities

6127116EBA104E238AD91949F3293B5F.description:
Eighteen to
Twenty-Four Months: Show awareness of being seen
by others such as repeating
an action when someone is
watching (E.g. Whenever she
sees a camera, Ruby smiles and
poses.)

DF6E6A16FDB94A07BAE9F9F64426F3FD.description:
Nine Months to
Eighteen Months
: Show likes and dislikes in ways
that are consistent with the
family’s cultural expectations
(E.g. Brady vocalizes pleasure
while playing, but cries while
having a diaper changed.)

033D1C64B8824BD59EA4556AA12CFCDE.description:
Birth to
Nine Months: Smile or are comforted when
a trusted caregiver speaks
kindly to them
